    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_134282711" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/134282711" />
    <a title="Derek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/239943-derek"><img alt="Derek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1456073337p2/239943.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/134282711?book_show_action=true">Dec 09, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Derek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Derek" href="/user/show/239943-derek">Derek</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781844674718" href="/book/show/8170835-i-rigoberta-menchu">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer134282711" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8595507470378610901">I fully recognize that Menchu&apos;s voice--conversational, unpretentious, emphatic--is what draws most readers to <i>I, Rigoberta Menchu</i>. At the same time, I found it the most grating aspect of the book, full as it was of contradictions, superlatives, and simply repetitive insistences on the positive aspects of her culture and the crimes committed by her country during the Guatemalan Civil War. Which isn&apos;t to say, of course, that I don&apos;t think she has every right to tell this story; the crimes she righ</span>
  <span id="freeText8595507470378610901" style="display:none">I fully recognize that Menchu's voice--conversational, unpretentious, emphatic--is what draws most readers to <i>I, Rigoberta Menchu</i>. At the same time, I found it the most grating aspect of the book, full as it was of contradictions, superlatives, and simply repetitive insistences on the positive aspects of her culture and the crimes committed by her country during the Guatemalan Civil War. Which isn't to say, of course, that I don't think she has every right to tell this story; the crimes she rightfully describes are horrifying, and conveying the intricacies of her culture had a practical purpose, given that she was seeing so many of her people die. But there's something missing on just about every page here for me, something that I think is a result of that voice. There were places that warranted more reflection, places where a deeper understanding of the limitations and contradictions of that Quiche culture might have been explored (yes, alongside the positives), but these things rarely happened. And the book suffers for it.<br /><br />The first half of the book is a lengthy discussion on her Quiche Indian culture, and the difficulties faced in being an Indian in Guatemala. There's of course some narrative, but this is mostly an anthropoligically valuable description of her village in the mountains. The second half shows Menchu being far more specific, describing her particular story and how she came to see her family killed, and the influence that these events had on her decision to join the CUC and the movement started in her father's name. All good information of course, but structuring the book this way lessens considerably the impact of either section because each piece informs the other in ways that would have been far more illuminating if mixed. It's difficult to say how much of this is the fault of the interviewer, Elisabeth Burgos-Debray, but the end result is the same: a book that drags far more than it ought to, given the import of Menchu's message.<br /><br />I won't spend any time here reviewing the narrative's inaccuracies uncovered in the 1990s by David Stoll. This isn't because I don't think they are relevant (by god, they are), but rather because they've been much more thoroughly explored elsewhere; there's little I can add to that conversation. Needless to say, these inaccuracies also greatly detract from the book's merit, even more so than my comparatively minor complaints against superlatives and narrative structuring. Is the book worth picking up? I suppose. But there are serious drawbacks to consider, and much of what Menchu claims seems to need a healthy dose of salt to be swallowed. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8595507470378610901" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


